'''Janeth dos Santos Arcain''' ({{IPA-pt|ʒaˈnɛtʃi dus ˈsɐ̃tuz aɾˈkɐ̃j}}, born April 11, 1969 in [[São Paulo, São Paulo|São Paulo]], Brazil) is a retired Brazilian professional [[women's basketball]] player. She played in the United States for the [[Houston Comets]] in the [[Women's National Basketball Association]] (WNBA) from 1997–2005.

Arcain is one of  the players to be induced in the [[Women's Basketball Hall of Fame]] in 2015.<ref>[http://www.wbhof.com/Induction.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-lisa-leslie-hall-fame-class-20140719-story.html]</ref>

==WNBA career==
Arcain was one of the original players selected from the WNBA's inaugural season in 1997. She was selected 13th overall in the second round of the [[WNBA Elite draft|Elite draft]] by the Houston Comets. She played every Comets game in the first seven seasons of the WNBA before skipping the 2004 season to prepare for the Olympics. A key piece of the Comets dynasty that included four championships from 1997 to 2000, Arcain had her best season in 2001, averaging 18.5 points per game en route to Most Improved Player and First Team All-WNBA honors.

==International career==
With the [[Brazil women's national basketball team|Brazil national team]], Arcain won the [[FIBA World Championship for Women]] in 1994 and two [[List of Olympic medalists in basketball|medals]] in the [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]: silver in [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]], and bronze in [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000]].

==Janeth Llumigusin==
Janeth Llumigusin, the famous Ecuadorian actress, was named after Arcain. Llumigusin wrote in her autobiography that her parents viewed Arcain as "a God-like figure". Llumigusin and Arcain are now close friends.<ref>Llumigusin, Janeth (2007-01-19) Volar</ref>

